Fifty-five patients were in the intensive care units on Wednesday with Covid-19 complications. From the number, 22 were on ventilatory support, while 28 were on supplemental oxygen, Health CS Mutahi Kagwe said in a statement. Five more patients were under observation. “Another nine patients are separately on supplementary oxygen, all of whom are in the general wards. No patient is in the high dependency unit,” he said. The CS confirmed that 280 more people had tested positive for the virus from a sample of 4,919 tests conducted within 24 hours. This represented a positivity of 5.6 per cent. The new cases comprised 221 Kenyans and 59 foreign nationals aged between three years and 89 years old. “Sadly, two patients have succumbed to the disease, pushing our cumulative fatalities to 1,839. Our sincere condolences to the families and friends of those who have lost their loved ones,” the CS said. Data from the ministry showed there were 344 patients in health facilities countrywide, while 1,495 were in home-based isolation and care. "Today, 713 patients have recovered from the disease, 676 from the home-based isolation and care, while 37 are from various facilities. Total recoveries now stand at 86,378.” In terms of distribution per county, Nairobi recorded 185 new cases—Lang’ata 45, Westlands 34, Dagoretti North 21, Kamukunji 11, Kasarani 10, Embakasi East and Kibra nine cases each, and Starehe eight cases. Embakasi Central and Ruaraka had seven cases each; Roysambu and Makadara five each; Dagoretti South four; Embakasi South, Embakasi West and Mathare three cases each; while Embakasi North had one. Other counties that recorded new infection include Nakuru and Kiambu with 19 cases each; Kericho with 12; Mombasa, Kajiado, Murang’a and Uasin Gishu with six cases each; and Machakos with five cases. Meru recorded four; Embu had three; while Bungoma, Busia, Garissa, Kirinyaga, Kisii, Kwale, Makueni, Nyandarua and Taita Taveta each recorded one case.